
@see https://duncanlock.net/blog/2021/11/09/styleable-inline-svg-icon-sprite-system-with-caching-fallback/

All icons for a page will be in a single SVG sprite file (sprite.svg)

Once the sprite is loaded, you can reference individual icons within the sprite using the <use> tag:

<svg class="icon">
  <use xlink:href="https://cdn.example.com/icons/sprite.svg#icon-home"></use>
</svg>

Why This Is Efficient

    Caching: The single sprite file can be cached by the browser or CDN, so subsequent page loads will use the cached version, further reducing load times.
    Reduced HTTP Overhead: Fewer requests mean less HTTP overhead, which improves page performance, especially on slower networks or devices.
    Scalability: Even if you add more icons to the sprite, the number of requests remains the same (just one for the sprite file).

    Styling Flexibility: Since the icons are inline SVGs, you can easily style them with CSS (e.g., change color, size, or add hover effects) using the fill, stroke, or width/height properties.
    Fallback Support: If the CDN fails, you can provide a local fallback sprite file, ensuring the icons still load.


